-- Guru Parampara Data
DELETE FROM guru_parampara;

An accomplished scholar, Vishnu Theertha authored foundational works such as the Samnyasapaddhati. He established a spiritual lineage through his disciples, Vyasa Theertha and Aniruddha Theertha, which evolved into the prestigious Sode Vadiraja and Subrahmanya Mathas. Tradition maintains that he remains in a state of living penance in the Western Ghats. It is prophesied that he will eventually reappear to recover the Sarvamula texts and re-establish the Dvaita philosophy.

Regarded as one of the Ruju deities, Vishnu Theertha’s life represents the pinnacle of spiritual discipline. His legacy is preserved through the worship of the Bhuvaraha and Hayagriva icons, symbolizing the continuity of his divine authority.');

His contribution to the tradition was marked by a rare synthesis of scholastic excellence and poetic mastery, playing a vital role in the intellectual expansion of the Dvaita school. Beyond his academic prowess, he was a virtuous administrator of the hierarchy, conducting the worship of its sacred icons with immense devotion.

Although historical records suggest he was a prolific author, his literary works have not survived to the present day. Sri Vyasa Theertha entered his Vrindavana in 1327 CE, leaving behind a legacy of piety and spiritual erudition.');

As a compassionate teacher, he traveled extensively on pilgrimages, offering spiritual counsel to the faithful and guiding seekers toward liberation from worldly anxieties. His tenure as the head of the Sode lineage lasted nine years, during which he significantly strengthened the intellectual and devotional foundations of the Matha. Sri Vedya Theertha entered Vrindavana in 1336 CE');

His reputation was built upon a steadfast commitment to the prescribed Vedic norms and an unwavering dedication to his spiritual duties. Throughout his ten-year tenure as the head of the Sode lineage, he served as a pillar of stability and popularity within the community. Sri Vedagarbha Theertha entered Vrindavana in 1346 CE, concluding a decade of influential spiritual leadership.');

Throughout his eight-year tenure, he traveled extensively to disseminate the true essence of the Shastras to the devout. His mission was defined by the propagation of Vedantic truths through direct, accessible discourse. Sri Varesha Theertha entered Vrindavana in 1354 CE, leaving a legacy of academic rigor and missionary zeal.');

Renowned for his oratorical skills, he frequently delivered discourses on the Bhagavata, where his melodic recitation of the Shlokas was said to immerse his audience in a deep stream of devotion. In a notable departure from common practice, Sri Vamana Theertha nominated his successor despite not yet reaching an advanced age. He held the tenure seat for a period of eight years before entering Vrindavana in 1362 CE');

Unlike many of his predecessors who traveled extensively, Sri Vasudeva Theertha preferred a life of contemplative stability. He spent the majority of his tenure in the sacred presence of Lord Krishna at Udupi, where he focused on delivering insightful lectures and teaching the deeper philosophical nuances of the Bhashya. After a seven-year pontificate, he entered Vrindavana in 1369 CE');

Attributing his success to the divine grace of Hari-Vayu-Guru, he excelled in both public debates and scholarly discourses. His tenure as the head of the Sode lineage lasted eight years, during which he significantly bolstered the intellectual defenses of the school. Sri Vedavyasa Theertha entered Vrindavana in 1377 CE');

Preferring the quietude of secluded environments, Sri Varaha Theertha dedicated his spiritual merits to the welfare of his faithful devotees. In a strategic move for the continuity of the lineage, he nominated and empowered his successor while still in middle age. His pontificate lasted nine years, concluding with his entry into Vrindavana in 1386 CE');

While tradition suggests he was a prolific author, his most significant extant work is Kavikarnamrutam, a scholarly commentary on the Vayustuti by Trivikrama Panditacharya. This work is highly regarded for its poetic sophistication and linguistic depth. Additionally, historical accounts attribute a commentary on Sri Madhvacharya’s Nakhastuti to him. Sri Vedatma Theertha presided over the tenure seat for twelve years, significantly enriching the intellectual heritage of the Matha before entering Vrindavana in 1398 CE');

A master of diverse arts and sciences, he was a formidable presence in the scholarly arena. During theological debates, he was renowned for his "stock and sample" replies—precise, instantaneous, and devastatingly effective arguments that consistently silenced his opponents. His intellectual agility and authoritative discourse left audiences stunned and further solidified the prestige of the Sode lineage. Sri Vishwavandya Theertha presided over the tenure seat for twenty-four years, entering Vrindavana in 1422 CE');

A pivotal historical moment involves his protection of a displaced king from the Chowta dynasty. Through intense meditation on Lord Bhuvaraha, Sri Ratnagarbha Theertha granted the king a divine vision and invoked the prtection of the Lord to defeat the enemies of the king. Furthermore, he miraculously solved a regional water scarcity by invoking Lord Varaha, whose movement created a perennial spring that remains visible today. Narala is also significant as the birthplace of the prominent deity Sri Bhutaraja (known locally as Naralattaya).

Sri Ratnagarbha Theertha is credited with a commentary on the Mahabharata Tatparya Nirnaya. Uniquely, he is said to have cast off his mortal coil through Yogic power in Narala prior to the passing of his Guru in 1422 CE');

Even while on pilgrimage, Vedanga Theertha remained committed to the pedagogical tradition, educating disciples in the sacred lores. He entered Vrindavana in 1441 CE at Bilagi, situated on the banks of the Soma (Aghanashini) River. This site later gained further significance when Sri Vadiraja Theertha interred a complete set of his own works there, consecrating the spot with icons of Lord Vedavyasa, Hanuman, and Garuda.');

His spiritual practice was characterized by constant immersion in the scriptures; he was known for his unique habit of reciting and chanting sacred texts even while walking, turning every moment into an act of worship. Sri Vidyapati Theertha presided over the lineage for eight years, upholding the spiritual standards of the tradition  before entering Vrindavana in 1449 CE');

A fearless ascetic, he often wandered alone in solitary contemplation. His spiritual authority was most notably demonstrated during a Paryaya festival in Udupi, where he used his mystic powers to effectively neutralize the disruptive attempts of his detractors. Sri Vishwandya Theertha presided over the lineage for nine years, entering Vrindavana in 1458 CE');

His life was a testament to disciplined observance and tireless advocacy for Sri Madhvacharya’s teachings. After a fruitful eight-year tenure as the head of the Sode lineage, he attained the holy feet of the Lord and entered Vrindavana in 1466 CE');

His seven-year period of leadership was marked by a deep internal focus on spiritual realization and the maintenance of the sacred traditions of the lineage . Historically, his tenure is of great significance as it directly precedes the arrival of one of the most towering figures in the Madhva tradition. Sri Vitthala Theertha entered Vrindavana in 1473 CE');

An expert in the Bhagavad Gita, he engaged in successful theological debates across the country. He was also revered for his mystical healing powers, famously curing a Brahmin named Narahari of a terminal illness and miraculously granting the power of speech and oratory to a mute celibate. Sri Varadaraja Theertha presided over the lineage for eight years before entering Vrindavana in 1481 CE His tomb is located adjacent to the Harihareshwara Temple in Kumbhasi.');

His most significant spiritual contribution was his role in the incarnation of Sri Vadiraja Theertha. Through divine communion with Lord Varaha, Vagisha Theertha foretold the birth of the Latavya Ruju deity to the devotee couple, Ramacharya and Gauri Devi. Following divine instructions, he initiated the young prodigy into the ascetic order, naming him Vadiraja Theertha.

Renowned for his mastery over time (Trikala-jnana), he offered spiritual relief to devotees through the power of consecrated Mantrakshata. He spent his final years in Udupi, dedicated to pedagogical pursuits. Sri Vagisha Theertha entered Vrindavana in 1518 CE after a transformative 37-year tenure. His shrine remains a center of miracles, famously granting the blessing of progeny to the Kuppannatantri couple, who later adorned the Vrindavana with a brass Kavacha (armor) in gratitude.');

After mastering the Shastras under Vidyanidhi and Vagisha Theertha, he embarked on extensive pilgrimages across India. These travels culminated in the composition of the  Theerthaprabandha, a unique Sanskrit travelogue detailing India’s sacred geography.

Sri Vadiraja’s life was defined by profound miracles and scholarly milestones. He was the only saint after Madhvacharya to visit Urdhvabadari, where, at the instruction of Lord Vedavyasa, he authored the Lakshalankara (a commentary on the Mahabharata). He also secured the Vyasamushti for the Madhyavata Matha and famously received the icon of Lord Hayagriva. His unique devotion included offering a special sweet dish (Hayagriva Maddi) to the Lord, who would personally accept the offering in a divine form.');

Recognizing the divine status of his preceptor, Sri Vedavedya Theertha introduced the Samapuja system, where Sri Vadiraja is worshipped alongside the incarnations of Vayu. He also instituted the daily Paraku proclamation, a tradition of chanting Vadiraja’s titles of praise during evening worship that remains in practice today. Tradition records a miraculous event where Vedavedya was granted a physical vision of his master at Sode, facilitated by Sri Bhutaraja. He presided over the lineage for 15 years before entering his holy Vrindavana at Sonda in 1616 CE, where his shrine rests beside that of his Guru.');

Throughout his thirteen years of ascetic life, Sri Vidyanidhi Theertha remained a significant figure, yet he stands as the only pontiff in this specific lineage who did not perform a Paryaya in Udupi. Anticipating his early departure, he followed Sri Vadiraja’s instructions to nominate a successor, Sri Vidyanidhi Theertha, in 1593. His tenure coincided with a unique historical period where four different pontiffs were present within the hierarchy between 1593 and 1598. Today, his Vrindavana is situated at Kumbhasi, resting beside the Vrindavana of Sri Varadaraja Theertha I.');

His tenure was marked by several miraculous events that solidified the spiritual prestige of the Sode Matha. When a massive stone pillar (Dhvajastambha) repeatedly failed to stand in front of the Trivikrama Temple, Vedanidhi Theertha successfully installed it only after inscribing the image of Sri Vadiraja in his Hamsarudha form, as directed in a vision. He also displayed supernatural authority by relocating a protective King Cobra from Madhyavata Matha to Sode, where the serpent’s presence is still recognized near the holy shrines. Vedanidhi Theertha conducted two biennial Paryayas in Udupi and is revered in the tradition as a divine soul destined to become the next Garuda. He entered his holy Vrindavana at Sode in 1648 CE after a 32-year tenure.');

During his leadership, he successfully performed the biennial Paryaya at Udupi from 1660 to 1661, upholding the ritualistic standards of the Sri Krishna Temple. Sri Varadaraja Theertha presided over the tenure seat for twenty-five years, guiding the community with a balanced focus on academic rigor and meditative service. He entered his holy Vrindavana in 1673 CE at  Theerthahalli, leaving behind a legacy of dedicated scholarship and spiritual stability.');

Following the tradition of his predecessors, Sri Vishwadhiraja Theertha performed the biennial Paryaya at Udupi during the years 1676 and 1677. During this significant period, he focused heavily on the academic propagation of the Dvaita school, teaching the Sarvamula and other foundational works to a dedicated group of pupils. His intellectual dominance was further showcased when he organized a prestigious assembly of scholars, where he successfully defeated opponents through advanced theological debate. He entered his holy Vrindavana at Sode in 1688 CE, with his shrine situated adjacent to the Mruttika-vrindavana of Sri Vrindavanacharya.');

Beyond his dialectical achievements, he contributed significantly to the devotional literature of the Matha through several extant works. Notable among these are the Sri Vadirajastuti, Sri Vadirajashtaka, Jayastotra, and Vadirajadhyanaprakara, which focus on the glorification and meditative visualization of Sri Vadiraja Theertha. He presided over the Sode lineage for eighteen years, guiding the community with scholarly rigor and administrative dedication. Sri Vadivandya Theertha entered his holy Vrindavana at Sode in 1706 CE, where his shrine is located adjacent to that of Sri Vedanidhi Theertha.');

Beyond his Vedantic expertise, Sri Vishwavandya Theertha possessed an exceptional mastery of Purvamimamsa (hermeneutics) and Vyakarana (grammar). His scholarly legacy includes a rare and authoritative work on Mimamsa titled Bhattabodhini, a contribution specifically highlighted by the later pontiff Sri Vishwottama Theertha. He successfully performed his biennial Paryaya at Udupi during the years 1708 and 1709. After a sixteen-year tenure as the head of the Sode lineage, he entered his holy Vrindavana in 1722 CE His shrine is located in Udupi, situated directly behind that of Sri Vagisha Theertha.');

In his final years, he intended to pen a commentary titled Vimalabodhini, but he ceased the work after a divine vision from Sri Vadiraja advised him to focus on meditation instead. He successfully performed the 1724–25 Krishna Paryaya in Udupi, maintaining the high ritualistic and academic standards of his lineage. After seventeen years of leadership, he entered his holy Vrindavana in 1739 CE, where his shrine remains a site of veneration in Udupi.');

During his biennial Paryaya at Udupi in 1740–1741, he delivered a monumental year-long discourse on the Bhagavata. His dialectical skills were equally impressive; he famously defeated Sridhara Sharma, a prominent Shrivaishnava scholar, in a scholarly debate centered on the concept of Bhakti. Under his leadership, the Matha’s prestige grew significantly, attracting numerous gifts and endowments from various royal families and devotees. Sri Vishwanidhi Theertha presided over the Sode lineage for fourteen years before entering his holy Vrindavana in 1753 CE His shrine is located in the serene village of Undaru (Innanje) in the Udupi district.');

A hallmark of his influence was his encounter with Diwan Poornayya of Mysore. Through intuitive vision, the Swamiji identified a golden Mantapa the Diwan had prepared, eventually persuading him to gift the masterpiece to the Udupi Krishna Matha for the Lord’s service. This golden shrine remained a central feature of the temple’s worship for many decades. Sri Vishwadhishwara Theertha entered his holy Vrindavana in 1803 CE at Undaru, resting beside his preceptor, Sri Vishwanidhi Theertha.');

Known popularly as the "Kenchagaru Swamiji," he was a figure of immense influence who even initiated King Ramavarma of Cochin into the Madhva fold. Despite his academic brilliance, which was compared to the fragrance of musk, he remained a devoted disciple, performing his biennial Paryaya in Udupi during 1788–1789 with his Guru’s permission. In the Vrindavanakhyana, he is referred to as "Vipraguru" or "Vitthala" (his birth name), and the text details his transition of spiritual responsibilities—specifically the Pacchotika or sacred case of deities—to his successor, Sri Vishwapriya Theertha.

Sri Vishwesha Theertha is said to have entered his holy Vrindavana in 1794 CE at Kenchagaru village near Honnavara, notably while his own Guru was still alive. His tenure, though marked by an early departure from the mortal world, left a legacy of intellectual excellence and royal patronage from the Keladi kings and other southern dynasties. His annual Aradhana is observed on the thirteenth day of the dark half of the month of Magha.');

Vrindavanacharya’s 62-year tenure was marked by four glorious biennial Paryayas in Udupi. Despite receiving royal honors—including an emerald Mantapa from Mummadi Krishnaraja Wodeyar—he maintained extreme Vairagya (detachment), famously appearing even in royal durbars wearing only a loincloth. His intellectual mastery was matchless; he taught hundreds of scholars and commissioned foundational commentaries on the Akhyana.

His life was replete with miracles: he saved a drowning devotee in the Kaveri, turned ocean water sweet at Rameswaram for Achamana, and increased food quantities through sacred words. He also reconfirmed the Samatva worship of Vadiraja with Lord Vayu. Entering Vrindavana in 1865 at age 91, his shrine in Udupi features a carved Brahmin figure, signifying his past identity. Tradition acclaims him as the divine soul destined to become Indra in the next Kalpa.');

Swamiji’s tenure was defined by his fierce defense of the Siddhanta. When the Rujutva status of Sri Vadiraja was challenged at a convention in Madras in 1884, he swiftly countered by organizing a mass meeting in Udupi and publishing the seminal work Rujutvachandrodaya. This book became a foundational authority for establishing the divine status of Sri Vadiraja. His academic excellence earned him international recognition, including a formal letter of praise from Queen Victoria, which remains a preserved document at the Sode Matha.

During his 34-year leadership, he performed two biennial Paryayas (1868–69 and 1884–85) and oversaw significant renovations within the inner shrine of the Sri Krishna Temple. Sri Vishwadhisha Theertha entered his holy Vrindavana in 1889 CE at Udupi, located directly behind the shrine of his Guru. Such was his impact that a local holiday was declared on the day of his passing.');

A pioneer in modern education, Swamiji established the Vishnumurthy Hayavadanaswamy High School in Innanje—the first such institution in the region—which has since flourished into a leading Pre-University College. His intellectual leadership was further cemented through the organization of the "Yuktimallika Sourabha Prakashini", a long-running scholarly assembly held at the Sri Ananteshwara Temple to promote the works of Sri Vadiraja.

During his three successful biennial Paryayas, he renovated the Vrindavanashala in Udupi. He enjoyed significant royal patronage, receiving honors and substantial grants for the Krishna Matha from King Ramavarma of Cochin and Maharaja Krishnarajendra Wodeyar of Mysore. Remarkably, he was also an expert Ayurvedic physician who formulated "Hayagrivataila", a medicated oil for rheumatic pain that remains a signature preparation of the Sode Matha today. Sri Vishwendra Theertha entered his holy Vrindavana in 1943 at Udyavara, leaving a legacy of academic patronage, medical service, and educational reform.');

His administrative and spiritual legacy is immense. He performed four biennial Paryayas in Udupi (1948–1997), during which he organized the 500th birth anniversary of Sri Vadiraja and constructed the Vadiraja Mandira near the Krishna Temple. At Sode, which he considered his ultimate sanctuary, he executed historical renovations, established the Bhavisameera Gurukula, and fulfilled a divine instruction by having the entire Vrindavanakhyana inscribed in stone within the newly built Akhyanamandira. An ardent researcher, he personally collected over two thousand rare manuscripts, preserving them for future generations of scholars.

Beyond the Shastras, Sri Vishwottama Theertha was a compassionate social reformer. He upgraded the educational facilities at Innanje to a Pre-University College and established a large-scale Goshala at Huvinakere to protect aged cows. Known for his "serene light" and healing Mantrakshata, he served as a spiritual refuge for thousands. He peacefully departed the mortal world in 2007 while uttering the name of Rama, having lived a life of total surrender to Lord Hayagriva and Sri Vadiraja.');

A visionary leader, Swamiji initiated the construction of Rajadhama at Sode and established the Srimadvrindavanacharya Samshodhana hagu Prakashana Kendra to preserve and publish thousands of ancient manuscripts. To support contemporary scholars, he launched the Vidwatsambhavane scheme and the religious magazine Tattvamallika. Extending the Matha’s educational legacy, he founded the Shri Madhva Vadiraja Institute of Technology and Management (SMVITM) to provide high-quality technical education to rural students.

His first biennial Paryaya (2012–2014) was historic, featuring the commissioning of a new Brahmaratha for Lord Krishna and the publication of Vadiraja’s Yuktimallika in ten comprehensive volumes. He also oversaw the translation of the Mahabharatha Tatparya Nirnaya with Vadiraja’s commentary. Known for his Vaksiddhi and deep devotion to the Rujutva of Sri Vadiraja, he continues to lead the Matha with a focus on Annadana, scholarly discourses, and social welfare programs, including aid for the underprivileged and medical support.');

